question: similarity_feedback

Experiment instructions

Description: In this experiment, you will listen to different styles of jazz played on the piano. Some are real performances, and others are generated with artificial intelligence.

Task: You will be asked several questions about each performance. For instance, you might be asked to rate how creative or diverse the performance was, or to suggest a potential style of jazz for the performance.

Genres: You will hear three different styles of jazz during the experiment.

  • Avant-Garde: this might include performances by pianists like Paul Bley and Geri Allen
  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.
  • When rating a performance, try to focus on the quality of the musical composition and not on the quality of the virtual instruments or the music production mix.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

metadata_:
{'time_taken': 86.174, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 10, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-12T11:54:30.615Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-12T11:54:30.657Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-12T11:54:30.657Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-12T11:54:30.662Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-12T11:54:30.662Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': '

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

Experiment instructions

Description: In this experiment, you will listen to different styles of jazz played on the piano. Some are real performances, and others are generated with artificial intelligence.

Task: You will be asked several questions about each performance. For instance, you might be asked to rate how creative or diverse the performance was, or to suggest a potential style of jazz for the performance.

Genres: You will hear three different styles of jazz during the experiment.

  • Avant-Garde: this might include performances by pianists like Paul Bley and Geri Allen
  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

metadata_:
{'time_taken': 13244.507, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 10, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T17:10:13.679Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T17:10:16.923Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T17:10:16.923Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T17:10:16.927Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T17:10:16.927Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': '

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

{'time_taken': 44.838, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 10, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T15:31:53.808Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T15:31:53.918Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T15:31:53.920Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T15:31:53.925Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T15:31:53.925Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': '

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

Experiment instructions

Description: In this experiment, you will listen to different styles of jazz played on the piano. Some are real performances, and others are generated with artificial intelligence.

Task: You will be asked several questions about each performance. For instance, you might be asked to rate how creative or diverse the performance was, or to suggest a potential style of jazz for the performance.

Genres: You will hear three different styles of jazz during the experiment.

  • Avant-Garde: this might include performances by pianists like Paul Bley and Geri Allen
  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.
  • When rating a performance, try to focus on the quality of the musical composition and not on the quality of the virtual instruments or the music production mix.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

"}, 'control': {}}

metadata_:
{'time_taken': 17.549, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 10, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T13:02:06.569Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T13:02:06.796Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T13:02:06.796Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T13:02:06.801Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-10T13:02:06.801Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': '

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

question: feedback
answer: I disagree with some of the genre classifications. As a performing jazz musician, I felt some of the avant-garde pieces were just as easily a good improvisation over a straight-ahead jazz tune. I expected the AI-generated examples of avant-garde to be more 'out there' like the played ones were. Also, I thought all the AI pieces had creative musical merit, only because the AI was referencing the body of recorded jazz, which, by nature, is highly creative. I would be fascinated to learn the prompts that the AI was given and the knowledge of jazz theory, which would give it a finite vocabulary.

Experiment instructions

Description: In this experiment, you will listen to different styles of jazz played on the piano. Some are real performances, and others are generated with artificial intelligence.

Task: You will be asked several questions about each performance. For instance, you might be asked to rate how creative or diverse the performance was, or to suggest a potential style of jazz for the performance.

Genres: You will hear three different styles of jazz during the experiment.

  • Avant-Garde: this might include performances by pianists like Paul Bley and Geri Allen
  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.
  • When rating a performance, try to focus on the quality of the musical composition and not on the quality of the virtual instruments or the music production mix.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

"}, 'control': {}}

metadata_:
{'time_taken': 45.934, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 10, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-09T20:14:57.994Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-09T20:14:58.435Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-09T20:14:58.435Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-09T20:14:58.440Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-09T20:14:58.440Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': '

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

Experiment instructions

Description: In this experiment, you will listen to different styles of jazz played on the piano. Some are real performances, and others are generated with artificial intelligence.

Task: You will be asked several questions about each performance. For instance, you might be asked to rate how creative or diverse the performance was, or to suggest a potential style of jazz for the performance.

Genres: You will hear three different styles of jazz during the experiment.

  • Avant-Garde: this might include performances by pianists like Paul Bley and Geri Allen
  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.
  • When rating a performance, try to focus on the quality of the musical composition and not on the quality of the virtual instruments or the music production mix.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

"}, 'control': {}}

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.
  • When rating a performance, try to focus on the quality of the musical composition and not on the quality of the virtual instruments or the music production mix.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

Experiment instructions

Description: In this experiment, you will listen to different styles of jazz played on the piano. Some are real performances, and others are generated with artificial intelligence.

Task: You will be asked several questions about each performance. For instance, you might be asked to rate how creative or diverse the performance was, or to suggest a potential style of jazz for the performance.

Genres: You will hear three different styles of jazz during the experiment.

  • Avant-Garde: this might include performances by pianists like Paul Bley and Geri Allen
  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.
  • When rating a performance, try to focus on the quality of the musical composition and not on the quality of the virtual instruments or the music production mix.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

"}, 'control': {}}

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

metadata_:
{'time_taken': 41.696, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 9.05, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-07T14:50:57.446Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-07T14:50:57.465Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-07T14:50:57.465Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-07T14:50:57.471Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-07T14:50:57.472Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': "

Experiment instructions

Description: In this experiment, you will listen to different styles of jazz played on the piano. Some are real performances, and others are generated with artificial intelligence.

Task: You will be asked several questions about each performance. For instance, you might be asked to rate how creative or diverse the performance was, or to suggest a potential style of jazz for the performance.

Genres: You will hear three different styles of jazz during the experiment.

  • Avant-Garde: this might include performances by pianists like Paul Bley and Geri Allen
  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.
  • When rating a performance, try to focus on the quality of the musical composition and not on the quality of the virtual instruments or the music production mix.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

"}, 'control': {}}

metadata_:
{'time_taken': 76.014, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 9.05, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-07T14:48:33.158Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-07T14:48:33.930Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-07T14:48:33.930Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-07T14:48:33.938Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-07T14:48:33.938Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': '

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

metadata_:
{'time_taken': 22.146, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 10, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T20:00:07.054Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T20:00:07.056Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T20:00:07.056Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T20:00:07.061Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T20:00:07.061Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': "

Experiment instructions

Description: In this experiment, you will listen to different styles of jazz played on the piano. Some are real performances, and others are generated with artificial intelligence.

Task: You will be asked several questions about each performance. For instance, you might be asked to rate how creative or diverse the performance was, or to suggest a potential style of jazz for the performance.

Genres: You will hear three different styles of jazz during the experiment.

  • Avant-Garde: this might include performances by pianists like Paul Bley and Geri Allen
  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.
  • When rating a performance, try to focus on the quality of the musical composition and not on the quality of the virtual instruments or the music production mix.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

"}, 'control': {}}

metadata_:
{'time_taken': 1.11, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 10, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T19:59:29.275Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T19:59:29.280Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T19:59:29.280Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T19:59:29.284Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T19:59:29.284Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': '

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

Experiment instructions

Description: In this experiment, you will listen to different styles of jazz played on the piano. Some are real performances, and others are generated with artificial intelligence.

Task: You will be asked several questions about each performance. For instance, you might be asked to rate how creative or diverse the performance was, or to suggest a potential style of jazz for the performance.

Genres: You will hear three different styles of jazz during the experiment.

  • Avant-Garde: this might include performances by pianists like Paul Bley and Geri Allen
  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.
  • When rating a performance, try to focus on the quality of the musical composition and not on the quality of the virtual instruments or the music production mix.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

"}, 'control': {}}

metadata_:
{'time_taken': 7.488, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 10, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T17:32:54.107Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T17:32:54.203Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T17:32:54.204Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T17:32:54.209Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T17:32:54.209Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': '

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

{'time_taken': 4.178, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 10, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T15:09:44.721Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T15:09:44.727Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T15:09:44.728Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T15:09:44.753Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-05T15:09:44.753Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': "

Experiment instructions

Description: In this experiment, you will listen to different styles of jazz played on the piano. Some are real performances, and others are generated with artificial intelligence.

Task: You will be asked several questions about each performance. For instance, you might be asked to rate how creative or diverse the performance was, or to suggest a potential style of jazz for the performance.

Genres: You will hear three different styles of jazz during the experiment.

  • Avant-Garde: this might include performances by pianists like Paul Bley and Geri Allen
  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.
  • When rating a performance, try to focus on the quality of the musical composition and not on the quality of the virtual instruments or the music production mix.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

"}, 'control': {}}

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

Experiment instructions

Description: In this experiment, you will listen to different styles of jazz played on the piano. Some are real performances, and others are generated with artificial intelligence.

Task: You will be asked several questions about each performance. For instance, you might be asked to rate how creative or diverse the performance was, or to suggest a potential style of jazz for the performance.

Genres: You will hear three different styles of jazz during the experiment.

  • Avant-Garde: this might include performances by pianists like Paul Bley and Geri Allen
  • Mainstream or "Straight-Ahead": this might include performances by pianists like Oscar Peterson and Bill Evans
  • Traditional & Early: this might include performances by pianists like Art Tatum and Teddy Wilson

Advice: There are no right or wrong answers: give us your overall impression of the performances you just heard and try to be consistent with how you answer.

  • Take as much time as you need to answer the questions.
  • Some performances may sound unusual, but you should do the best to complete the task regardless.
  • Some performances may start and end abruptly. This is normal and you should not let it affect your ratings.
  • When rating a performance, try to focus on the quality of the musical composition and not on the quality of the virtual instruments or the music production mix.

Press 'Next' when you are ready to continue.

"}, 'control': {}}

metadata_:
{'time_taken': 38.145, 'platform': 'anon', 'download_speed_megabits_per_sec': 10, 'event_log': [{'eventType': 'trialConstruct', 'localTime': '2025-06-04T16:34:21.487Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialPrepare', 'localTime': '2025-06-04T16:34:21.708Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'trialStart', 'localTime': '2025-06-04T16:34:21.709Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'responseEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-04T16:34:21.717Z', 'info': None}, {'eventType': 'submitEnable', 'localTime': '2025-06-04T16:34:21.718Z', 'info': None}], 'prompt': {'text': '

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}

Information sheet

Before you decide to take part in this study it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully and discuss it with others if you wish.

Purpose of the study. Machine learning is changing the ways we think about art and music. In this experiment, we are interested in understanding perceptions of jazz music generated by artificial intelligence. You will listen to a variety of jazz performances and rate them according to several different criteria.

What is the procedure? The experiment takes place in your web browser. You will be asked to perform simple tasks using your keyboard or mouse while listening to sounds.

Do I have to take part? Taking part is entirely voluntary. Refusal or withdrawal will involve no penalty or loss, now or in the future.

How long does the experiment last? The full experiment should last approximately 15 minutes, though individual times will vary.

Benefits of taking part. After completing the experiment, you will have the option of providing your email address to be entered into a draw with a chance of winning a £50 Amazon gift voucher. The prize draw will be made once data collection for the experiment has finished.

Confidentiality. If you provide your email to be entered into the prize draw, this will be stored on a secure computer server and removed once data collection for this experiment has ended. No other personal details (e.g. name, contact data) will be collected at any stage, so your data will be anonymous throughout. This anonymous data may eventually be shared in public data repositories, conferences, and scientific journals.

Ethical review. The project has been approved by the University of Cambridge Faculty of Music Ethics Committee. We are conscious of the ethical issues that are raised by training machines to generate music. Our models are released under non-commercial licenses. This means that other people will not be able to profit by using our model to create their own music to sell, nor will they be able to sell any of the music we have generated using these models. Ultimately, this research is about understanding the kinds of music generated by artificial intelligence, and not about using artificial intelligence to replace musicians.

Contact for further information. If you have further queries about this experiment, please contact Huw Cheston at hwc31@cam.ac.uk.

'}, 'control': {}}
